Exploring Bikeshare data in R¶

The objective of this project is to explore data related to bike share systems for three major cities in the United StatesChicago, New York City, and Washington. For this, several R libraries will be used, making use of the different functions that help with the analysis and processing of data based on this language. For example, ggplot, lemon and visdat will be used for visualizations, while fasDummies, dplyr and plyr will be used for the manipulation of data.

Table of Content:¶

Introduction¶

As mentioned by the National Association of City Transportation Officials (NACTO), the US bike-share system is growing continuously, for example between 2016 and 2017 there was an increment of 25%. This increment in the use of the system is a consequence of the launch of several major new bike-share systems. Since 2010, more than 123 trips have been taken on bike share bikes in the U.S. Therefore, it is important to understand the data related with the bike share system to find new opportunities that could increase incomes of a similar business.

Preprocessing the dataframe¶

Content format¶

In this section, the names for the dataframe columns are changed, to be more descriptive and shorter. Besides, non-numerical categorical variables are converted to integers and dummy variables, for a more understandable processing and analysis of the data. Lastly, if some of the dataframes related to the loaded data miss some of the features contained in the rest of the data frames, those are added having as content nan values. This is possible using a custom function called PrePro1.

Creating dictionaries, list of lists, to retrieve the original names variables and content.

Removing NaN values¶

In this section are remove undefined values presented in the created dataframes, with the exception of the gender and birth year features. Two different types of undefined values are removed:

  • Undefined values represented as strings, such as "NULL" or "NA"
  • nan and null values presented, such as NULL and NA

Undefined values present in the gender and birth year related features are maintained since those are an indication that only users who are subscribed provided this information. Removing rows related with those features is the same as removing all data related to users that are not subscribed to the bike share system. Moreover, features represented as non-numerical values are converted to integers.

The removing of undefined values is possible using a custom function named PrePro2, such that:

In [8]:
df.CHI <- PrePro2(df.CHI, names(df.CHI)[seq(3,length(names(df.CHI)))])
df.NY <- PrePro2(df.NY, names(df.NY)[seq(3,length(names(df.NY)))])
df.WA <- PrePro2(df.WA, names(df.WA)[seq(3,length(names(df.WA))-2)])

Creating features¶

Additional features are created for a better understanding of the sharing bike system. To be more specific, the travel_type feature is added, which classifies using 4 different levels the duration of the use of the bike by the users. In this case, the levels are defined by the TimeRate variables, presented in the next cell. Each of the variables defines the limit in the use of the bikes for the classification. This is possible using a custom function named PrePro3, as follow:

In [11]:
TimeRate1 <- 5  
TimeRate2 <- 15
TimeRate3 <- 30
TimeRate4 <- 45
df.CHI <- PrePro3(df.CHI, TimeRate1, TimeRate2, TimeRate3, TimeRate4)
df.NY <- PrePro3(df.NY, TimeRate1, TimeRate2, TimeRate3, TimeRate4)
df.WA <- PrePro3(df.WA, TimeRate1, TimeRate2, TimeRate3, TimeRate4)

Exploring the data¶

Data distributions¶

In this section are presented the distribution of the use of time for the three created and modified dataframes. It can be seen that the distributions represent gaussian processes but are skewed, given some bias towards the long tails. Therefore, it is required the reduction of outliers, to have a better representation of the gaussian processes.

Features tendencies - Boxplots¶

Removing outliers¶

The outliers are removed based on a custom function called Rem_outliers, which calculate the 1st and 3rth quartiles for removing data located outside the IQR range:

In [14]:
df.CHI <- Rem_Outiers(df.CHI, 'Duration_Sec')
df.NY <- Rem_Outiers(df.NY, 'Duration_Sec')
df.WA <- Rem_Outiers(df.WA, 'Duration_Sec')

Tendency of the bike share system located in Chicago¶

The use of shared bikes in Chicago presents three different behaviours, related to three different periods of time, monthly, daily and hourly. It can be observed that the use of the bike system increase each month, probably related with summer holiday or probably because the system is more known that on earlier dates. On the other hand, by week, it can be seen that the use of bikes increases, closing to the last days of the week, especially the weekends. Furthermore, the most used hours are from 9 in the morning to 5 in the afternoon. The use of the bike share system is measured using the variance and mean and the IQR values for each of the mentioned periods of time. The mentioned information can be seen in the following figure:

In [15]:
PlotBoxplots(df.CHI)

Tendency of the bike share system located in New York

The exploration of data related with the bike share system located in New York presents a similar behaivor as the bike share system located in Chicago. The system has been used more the in June and Jule and is used more on the weekens and every day between 9 in the morning and 7 in the evening. Nonetheless, it presented a difference, a high use of the system daily between 12 in the nigh and 3 in the morning.

In [16]:
PlotBoxplots(df.NY)

Tendency of the bike share system located in Washington¶

The bike-share system present in Washington presents a similar behaviour monthly and daily as the previously presented cases. However, when exploring the use of the system by the hour it can be seen that the system is used more between the 0 and 7 hours, in comparison with the other system located at different cities. It also presents a peak between 10 and 17 hours, as the previous cases.

In [17]:
PlotBoxplots(df.WA)

Q1 - Routes for the uses of the bikes?¶

An additional characteristic to investigate is the relation between the origin and the destination of the users. This could help us to understand where the bikes are used more and why the differences in the duration of time for the uses of the bikes. Thus, the three dataframes related the cities of interest will be analyzed based on the features Origin, Destination and on the created feature Travel_Type. For this, it will be used the face_wrap ggplot characteristics. The stations that represent the origin and destination of the users are represented as integers, each of is used as the station names. Moreover, each of the numbers in which are divided the visualisation represents different periods of time for the use of bikes, such that:

  • 1.- Less or equal to 5 minutes
  • 2.- More than 5 minutes but less than 15 minutes
  • 3.- More than 15 minutes but less than 30 minutes
  • 4.- More than 30 minutes

The general statistics presented below show us the characteristics of the users of the bike share system in the cities of interest. For example, the number of stations where the bikes are rented and delivered, and the times of use for them. It also presents the number of users classified depending on the amount of time they use their bikes.

Chicago routes¶

In Chicago, it can be seen that most of the users of the bike share system use their bikes more than 5 minutes but less than 15 minutes, and most of their routers are among stations represented as integers 1 to 150. The remaining users use their bikes less than 5 min and some of them more than 15 but less than 30 minutes. However, the remaining users are distributed mostly between station 1 to 200.

New York routes¶

In New York, there is a bigger use of the bike share system. Most of them, as in the previous case, most of the users use their bikes more than 5 minutes but less than 15 minutes, and move between stations 1 to 400. The second bigger group of users use their bikes more than 15 minutes but less than 30 and is not that clear the most frequent routes for them. The last big group use their bikes less than 5 minutes, and there is not a clear route that is more used than the rest.

Washington routes¶

The bike-share system in Washington presents a more uniform use than in the previous case. There are three bigger groups of users, two of them travelling among similar stations. The first big group are users that use the bikes less than five minutes and move between stations 1 to 250. The rest of the bigger, users that use the bikes more than 5 minutes but less than 15 and more than 15 but less than 30. The users in both groups move among stations 1 to 290.

Q2 - Characteristics of the subscribers?¶

This section explores differences between the characteristics of the subscribers' users, such as their gender and the year of birth. This is possible using the distribution of users that highlight the differences between the mentioned characteristics, as presented in the next figure.

Chicago subscribers¶

It can be seen that the behaviour of the use of bikes is the same for both genders, but not the number of users. This is the same for the age of the users, both genders present a similar distribution, but with a difference. As a conclusion, there are not highlighted features that help us to understand better the use of the bike share system when comparing the gender of the subscribers of the system.

`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Q3 - Differences between customers and subscribers?¶

The last feature to analyze is the difference in the behaviour of the use of bikes between the subscriber and non-subscriber users. For this, both users will be cluster to understand better their preferences. This will be possible using k-means to cluster the users, after finding the optimal number of centres for the clustering relying in the Elbow method. The Elbow method is implemented using the custom function ElbowFunct, which rely on the k-means R function to calculate the score for a specific number of centres selected. However, the implementation of the method is omitted for clarity within the notebook. Nonetheless, the optimal number of centres for the clustering, for all dataframes, is 10.

Chicago users¶

After grouping the users it can be seen that both types of users, subscribers and costumers, have different behaviours. This can be observed better when comparing the time for the use of the bikes and the stations of origin and destination. However, both of them have specific behaviours, which can help the system to improve the use of bikes based o that, for example, having more bikes on specific stations.

Conclusions¶

It can be concluded that the data provided for this analysis is enough to have an idea of how the bike-share systems behave. However, more information is required for a deeper analysis, one in which will be possible to forecast the use of bikes in the system. For this, it will be required prices, amount of time for the use of the bikes, the distance between stations, number of bikes available at each station, amount of time since the user became a subscriber, condition of the bikes at the stations, among others. Whit this information it will be possible to forecast the cost of operating each of the stations and which station to expand to increase the bike share system.
